ely than lac. Yajna is cosmologically obligatory — built into the fabric of creation, transactional with divine beings who maintain the cosmos. OE *lac* is semantically broader: it covers secular prizes, Christian relic-veneration, and pagan placation. In Juliana, *lac* is propitiatory (an appeasement-gift to avert divine anger), not a cosmic-contractual feeding of gods. In Elene, *lac* is a reverently received divine gift, with no destruction at all. The ritual logics differ on two axes: (1) **cosmological necessity** — yajna is ontologically required by the structure of creation; *lac* in its ritual uses is situationally urgent but not cosmologically mandated; (2) **semantic range** — yajna is a technical term for Vedic fire-sacrifice to gods; *lac* covers gifts, prizes, tribute, and offerings across secular and sacred registers. 'Sacrifice' is an acceptable rough gloss for the Juliana *lac*, but it misfires for Elene and Wulf-and-Eadwacer. For yajna it is close but still undersells the cosmic dimension. The two words share an overlap (ritual gift to a divine power) but diverge in the degree to which the offering constitutes a cosmological mechanism versus a personal/political act of appeasement.",
